ot the whole story. In this book, Timothy B. Neary reveals the history of Bishop Bernard Sheil’s Catholic Youth Organization (CYO), which brought together thousands of young people of all races and religions from Chicago’s racially segregated neighborhoods to take part in sports and educational programming. Tens of thousands of boys and girls participated in basketball, track and field, and the most popular sport of all, boxing, which regularly filled Chicago Stadium with roaring crowds. The history of Bishop Sheil and the CYO shows a cosmopolitan version of American Catholicism, one that is usually overshadowed by accounts of white ethnic Catholics aggressively resisting the racial integration of their working-class neighborhoods. By telling the story of Catholic-sponsored interracial cooperation within Chicago, Crossing Parish Boundaries complicates our understanding of northern urban race relations in the mid-twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAfrican American youthxIllinoisxChicago. 0aAfrican American youthzIllinoiszChicago. 0aAfrican American youth. 0aAfrican AmericansxHistoryx20th centuryxIllinoisxChicago. 0aAfrican AmericanszIllinoiszChicagoxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican Americans. 0aCatholic youthxIllinoisxChicago. 0aCatholic youthzIllinoiszChicago. 0aCatholic youth. 0aParishesxHistoryx20th centuryxIllinoisxChicago. 0aParisheszIllinoiszChicagoxHistoryy20th century. 0aParishes. 0aRace relationsxReligious aspects. 0aRace relations. 0aSocial actionxHistoryx20th centuryxIllinoisxChicago. 0aSocial actionzIllinoiszChicagoxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial action. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aBishop Bernard Sheil.  aCYO.  aCatholic Youth Organization.  aCatholic social teaching.  aChicago.  aJohn McGreevy.  ainterracial.